)

Visualizing jobs in Santa Clara county (SCC) that pay less than, or equal to, $1,250 per month.

lodes_pal <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlGnBu",
  domain = scc_od$CE01
)

leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = scc_od,
    fillColor = ~lodes_pal(CE01),

SFBI_Databse <- read_csv("SFBI Database.csv")

SNAP_access <- SFBI_Databse %>% rename(
  lat= "latitude (from locations) 2",
  long = "longitude (from locations) 2",
  zip = "Zip Code (from address) (from locations) 3"
) %>% filter(SFBI_Databse$taxonomy == "Groceries")

SNAP_coord <- SNAP_access %>% filter(!is.na(lat) & !is.na(long)) %>% filter(lat != "NA, NA" | long != "NA, NA") %>% filter(active == "Open")

SNAP_coord <- st_as_sf(SNAP_coord, coords = c("long","lat"), crs = 4326)

SNAP_coord <- SNAP_coord %>% filter(zip %in% scc_zips$ZCTA5CE10)

leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(
    data = SNAP_coord,
    radius = 1,
    label = ~Name
  )

Producing a map of SNAP-accessible grocery stores accessible within a 10-minute walking distance in SCC.

walk_10min <- mb_isochrone(
  SNAP_coord,
  profile = "walking",
  time = 10
)

SNAP_walk_10min <-
  SNAP_coord %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  cbind(walk_10min$geometry) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

leaflet() %>% 
  addMapboxTiles(
    style_id = "streets-v11",
    username = "mapbox"
  ) %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = SNAP_walk_10min,
    label = ~Name
  )
scc_bgs <- 
  block_groups("CA","085", cb = T, progress_bar = F) %>% 
  st_transform(26910) %>% 
  mutate(original_area = st_area(.))

scc_bg_isochrone_intersect <-
  scc_bgs %>% 
  st_intersection(
    SNAP_walk_10min %>% 
      st_union() %>% 
      st_transform(26910)
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    leftover_area = st_area(.),
    perc_area = leftover_area / original_area
  )
scc_job1 <- scc_od %>% select(h_bg, CE01, BLKGRPCE, AFFGEOID) %>% mutate(job_level = "<= $1,250/month") %>% rename(job_count = CE01)
scc_job2 <- scc_od %>% select(h_bg, CE02, BLKGRPCE, AFFGEOID) %>% mutate(job_level = "$1,250-$3,333/month") %>% rename(job_count = CE02)
scc_job3 <- scc_od %>% select(h_bg, CE03, BLKGRPCE, AFFGEOID) %>% mutate(job_level = ">= $3,333/month") %>% rename(job_count = CE03)

scc_bg_jobs <- rbind(scc_job1, scc_job2, scc_job3)

scc_jobs <- scc_bg_jobs %>% group_by(job_level) %>% summarize(job_count = sum(job_count)) %>% 
  mutate(
    perc = job_count/sum(job_count),
    group = "Full Job Count"
  )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
scc_SNAP_jobs <-
  scc_bg_jobs %>% 
  left_join(  
    scc_bg_isochrone_intersect %>% 
      st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
      select(AFFGEOID, cbg = GEOID, perc_area),
    by = "AFFGEOID"
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(perc_area)) %>% 
  mutate(
    job_perc = job_count * perc_area
  ) %>% 
  group_by(job_level) %>% 
  summarize(job_count = sum(job_count)) %>% 
  mutate(
    perc = job_count/sum(job_count),
    group = "Jobs within 10 min. walk of SNAP stores"
  )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
sum(scc_SNAP_jobs$job_count)/
  sum(scc_jobs$job_count)
## [1] 0.9214925

92% of jobs in SCC exist within a 10-minute walking distance of SNAP-eligible retailers.

The next portion of this analysis will investigate whether the prevalence of jobs in these SNAP-isochrones varies based on monthly earnings.

rbind(scc_jobs,scc_SNAP_jobs) %>% 
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = "", 
      y = perc, 
      fill = reorder(job_level,desc(job_level))
    )
  ) + 
  geom_bar(
    stat = "identity", 
    position = position_fill()
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = paste0(round(perc*100),"%")), 
    position = position_fill(vjust = 0.5)
  ) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  facet_wrap(~ group)  +
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    legend.position = 'bottom'
  ) + 
  guides(
    fill = guide_legend(nrow=3, byrow=TRUE)
  ) +
  labs(
    fill = "Jobs"
  )

From these two graphs, it appears that the composition of jobs by earnings is nearly the same across the county as it is within 10 minutes walking of SNAP stores, with a slight decrease in jobs earning greater than, or equal to, $3,333 per month. From this analysis, it is difficult to draw conclusions regarding accessibility to SNAP-eligible retailers based on jobs and their level of earnings, which I had imagined as a sort of supplement to household income information. Below, I conduct an equity analysis on the basis of household income form ACS data.

scc_bg_income <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs5",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "block group:*", 
    regionin = "state:06+county:085",
    vars = "group(B19001)"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(cbg = paste0(state,county,tract,block_group)) %>% 
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,county,tract,block_group,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2018_5yr %>% 
      select(name, label), 
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>% 
  select(-variable) %>% 
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"income"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(income)) %>% 
  mutate(
    income = case_when(
      income %in% c("Less than $10,000","$10,000 to $14,999","$15,000 to $19,999","$20,000 to $24,999") ~ "Less than $25,000",
      income %in% c("$25,000 to $29,999","$30,000 to $34,999","$35,000 to $39,999","$40,000 to $44,999","$45,000 to $49,999") ~ "$25,000 to $49,999",
      income %in% c("$50,000 to $59,999","$60,000 to $74,999") ~ "$50,000 to $74,999",
      TRUE ~ income
    )
  )
## Warning: Expected 3 pieces. Missing pieces filled with `NA` in 1075 rows [1, 18,
## 35, 52, 69, 86, 103, 120, 137, 154, 171, 188, 205, 222, 239, 256, 273, 290, 307,
## 324, ...].
scc_income <-
  scc_bg_income %>% 
  mutate(income = factor(income, levels = unique(scc_bg_income$income))) %>% 
  group_by(income) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  mutate(
    perc = estimate/sum(estimate),
    group = "Full Population"
  )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
scc_SNAP_income <-
  scc_bg_income %>% 
  mutate(income = factor(income, levels = unique(scc_bg_income$income))) %>% 
  left_join(
    scc_bg_isochrone_intersect %>% 
      select(cbg = GEOID, perc_area) %>% 
      st_set_geometry(NULL)
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(perc_area)) %>% 
  mutate(
    estimate = estimate * perc_area
  ) %>% 
  group_by(income) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  mutate(
    perc = estimate/sum(estimate),
    group = "Population within 10 min. walk of SNAP stores"
  )
## Joining, by = "cbg"
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
sum(scc_SNAP_income$estimate)/
  sum(scc_income$estimate)
## 0.5604207 [1]

An estimated 56% of the population of SCC is within a 10-minute walking distance of SNAP-eligible retailers.

rbind(scc_income,scc_SNAP_income) %>% 
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = "", 
      y = perc, 
      fill = reorder(income,desc(income))
    )
  ) + 
  geom_bar(
    stat = "identity", 
    position = position_fill()
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = paste0(round(perc*100),"%")), 
    position = position_fill(vjust = 0.5)
  ) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  facet_wrap(~ group)  +
  theme(
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    legend.position = 'bottom'
  ) + 
  guides(
    fill = guide_legend(nrow=3, byrow=TRUE)
  ) +
  labs(
    fill = "Household\nIncome"
  )

These pie charts suggests that SNAP-eligible retailers are serving lower-income residents (<= $99,900 HI) at a slightly higher proportion than higher-income residents (> $99,900 HI). While this is a positive result, it is unclear how many low-income residents are not accounted for this in analysis, and therefore, live outside an easily-accessible distance from affordable food options.
